The latest stable version is **MSTest 4.2.3**. Since you're on 3.8.0, this is a major version jump with several breaking changes. Here's what affects your code:

---

## Breaking Changes Affecting Your Project

### 1. `[ExpectedException]` is removed in v4

Your two test methods use `[ExpectedException(...)]`, which no longer exists. Replace with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()`:

```csharp
// Before
[ExpectedException(typeof(ArgumentNullException))]
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Validate(null);
}

// After
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
}
```

### 2. `Assert.IsTrue(true)` triggers warning MSTEST0032

Your `Validate_ValidInput_Succeeds` test has `Assert.IsTrue(true)` which will now emit a **warning** (promoted from Info in v4). Replace with a meaningful assertion or suppress.

### 3. Other notable v4 breaking changes (not directly hitting your code today, but worth knowing):

| Change | Impact |
|--------|--------|
| `TestMethodAttribute.Execute` → `ExecuteAsync` | Only if you have custom test method attributes |
| `ClassCleanupBehavior` enum removed | Only if you specify `ClassCleanupBehavior.EndOfClass` |
| `Assert.ThrowsException` removed | Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly` instead |
| `TestContext.Properties` is now `IDictionary<string, object>` | `.Contains()` → `.ContainsKey()` |
| `TestTimeout` enum removed | Use `int.MaxValue` directly |
| Dropped .NET < 8 support | You're on net8.0, so you're fine |
| Assert `message` + `params object[]` → just `message` | Use string interpolation |

---

## How to Fix Your Project

Update `TestProject.csproj`:
```xml
<PackageReference Include="MSTest" Version="4.2.3" />
```

Update `ValidationServiceTests.cs`:
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
}

[TestMethod]
public void Process_InvalidState_ThrowsInvalidOperation()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<InvalidOperationException>(() => Process());
}
```

